# Getting Started Guide

This guide will help you set up the AlgoMaster Online Judge development environment. You can choose to deploy all services with Docker Compose, or run only infrastructure (PostgreSQL, Redis) in Docker and run the backend/frontend locally for development.

---

## 1. Prerequisites

Before starting, ensure your system has the following tools installed:

| Tool | Version Requirements | Purpose | Installation |
|------|---------------------|---------|--------------|
| Docker + Docker Compose | Docker 20.10+, Compose V2 | One-click startup of all services (recommended) | [Docker Desktop](https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/) |
| Rust toolchain | 1.90.0 (edition 2021) | Compile and run API service and judge worker | `rustup install 1.90.0` |
| Node.js | >= 20 | Frontend build and development server | [nvm](https://github.com/nvm-sh/nvm) or [Node.js website](https://nodejs.org/) |
| npm | >= 9 | Frontend package manager (installed with Node.js) | Included with Node.js |
| psql (optional) | PostgreSQL 16+ client | Manual SQL queries and seed scripts | `brew install libpq` (macOS) or system package manager |

### Rust Toolchain Details

The project's Rust toolchain version is pinned via `backend/rust-toolchain.toml`:

```toml
[toolchain]
channel = "1.90.0"
components = ["rustfmt", "clippy"]
```

If you're using `rustup`, the correct version will be automatically selected when entering the `backend/` directory for compilation. First-time installation:

```bash
rustup install 1.90.0
rustup default 1.90.0
```

### System Requirements

- **Operating System**: macOS or Linux for development. The judge-worker's sandbox functionality relies on Linux cgroups/seccomp and can only run properly via Docker containers on macOS.
- **Memory**: At least 8 GB recommended (Docker running all services + Rust compilation requires significant memory)
- **Disk**: Approximately 5-10 GB for Rust compilation cache and Docker images

