## 5. Docker Compose One-Click Deployment

### 5.1 Start All Services

Docker Compose can start all services (PostgreSQL, Redis, API, Frontend, Judge Worker) with one command:

```bash
docker compose up -d --build
```

Build process takes approximately 5-10 minutes (Rust compilation is slow). Wait for all container health checks to pass:

```bash
docker compose ps
```

All services should show `healthy` status:

| Container Name | Port Mapping | Purpose |
|----------------|--------------|---------|
| `online-judge-postgres` | 5432:5432 | PostgreSQL 16 database |
| `online-judge-redis` | 6379:6379 | Redis 7 cache and message queue |
| `online-judge-api` | 3000:3000 | REST API + WebSocket server |
| `online-judge-frontend` | 5173:80 | Frontend static files (Nginx hosted) |
| `online-judge-feature-gateway` | 3001:3001 | Feature flag resolution service |
| `online-judge-judge-worker` | No external port | Code judging service |

### 5.2 Start Individual Services

If you only need to start certain services:

```bash
# Start only infrastructure
docker compose up -d postgres redis

# Start API (depends on postgres and redis)
docker compose up -d api

# Start frontend (depends on api)
docker compose up -d frontend

# Start judge worker (depends on postgres, redis, and api)
docker compose up -d judge-worker

# Start feature gateway
docker compose up -d feature-gateway
```

### 5.3 View Logs

```bash
# View all service logs
docker compose logs -f

# View specific service logs
docker compose logs -f api
docker compose logs -f judge-worker
```

### 5.4 Stop and Cleanup

```bash
# Stop all services (preserve data)
docker compose down

# Stop and delete data volumes (complete cleanup)
docker compose down -v

# Rebuild and start (after code changes)
docker compose up -d --build
```

### 5.5 Judge Worker Considerations

The judge worker container requires `SYS_PTRACE` and `SYS_ADMIN` kernel capabilities for cgroups sandbox isolation, already configured in `docker-compose.yml`:

```yaml
cap_add:
  - SYS_PTRACE
  - SYS_ADMIN
```

This works directly on Linux hosts. On macOS or Windows, Docker Desktop uses a virtual machine and these capabilities may be restricted - sandbox functionality may not work properly, but other features remain unaffected.

